| Test | Asserts | Citation |
|---|---|---|
| `test_total_order_per_experiment` | Two reads of the event log return events in the same order. | 05 §4.1 |
| `test_replay_from_cursor_zero_returns_all_events` | After driving N transitions, `GET /events?cursor=0` returns all N events. | 05 §4.4 |
| `test_replay_repeatable` | Repeated `GET /events?cursor=0` returns the same set across calls (replay is deterministic across reads). | 05 §4.4 |
| `test_subscribe_at_least_once_via_reconnect` | Open `GET /events/subscribe?cursor=N` and consume one event; reconnect with `cursor=N` (not the post-batch cursor) and observe the same event again. The chapter 05 §4.3 MUST is "deliver every appended event to every active subscriber at least once"; reconnect-with-prior-cursor is the test that an event remains delivered after a recover/restart. (Codex review round 1 finding 4.) | 05 §4.3 |
| `test_subscribe_long_poll_yields_event` | Open `GET /events/subscribe?cursor=N` then issue a transition; the long-poll returns the new event within the configured timeout. | 07 §6.2 |
| `test_subscribe_empty_batch_after_timeout` | Open subscribe against a quiescent log; after the server timeout, response is `{events: [], cursor: <unchanged>}`. The reference adapter's 2.0s timeout (§D) keeps this test fast. | 07 §6.2 |

